'''Chesham and Amersham''' is a [[United Kingdom constituencies|parliamentary constituency]] represented in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]]. It elects one [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) by the [[first past the post]] system of election.

It is a safe Conservative seat.

== Boundaries ==
The constituency entirely encompasses the large suburban towns of [[Chesham]] and [[Amersham]] in [[Buckinghamshire]], and outlying villages in the area.

== History ==
The area is a blend of pleasant and leafy [[Green Belt]] land and urban settings. There are rapid transport links to central London via the [[London Underground]].

As a result of the demographic makeup of the area, the constituency is solidly [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]], and the party holds almost a 30% majority, with almost 55% of the vote. The next biggest party is the Liberal Democrats, with just over 25% of the vote.

The area was formerly part of the larger [[South_Buckinghamshire (UK Parliament constituency)|South Buckinghamshire constituency]] before boundary changes came into effect for the 1974 General Elections.

== Members of Parliament ==
The current [[Member of Parliament]] for Chesham and Amersham is the Conservative [[Cheryl Gillan]]. She has been in this position since 1992.
* ''Constituency created'' ([[1974]])
* [[1974]] &mdash; [[1992]]: [[Ian Gilmour]], [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]
* [[1992]] &mdash; ''present'': [[Cheryl Gillan]], [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]

